<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-115-178  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 115 178.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC World  Feb 1989 v7 n2 p180(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Cut costs on CompuServe. (Tips andamp; Techniques)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Glossbrenner, Alfred.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Cost- and time-saving techniques for using the Compuserve on-lineinformation retrieval service are presented.andP;  The cheapest way touse Compuserve is to tie into it through the service's ownpacket-switching network.andP;  Users should select desired ChangePermanent Settings to maximize their time on-line.andP;  Softwareshould not be searched on-line; as much work as possible should bedone off-line.andP;  The XMODEM protocol should be avoided as it waswritten for PC-to-PC links, not for linking to a mainframe such asCompuserve's.andP;  The correct modem should be chosen; for example,the user would have to download 9Mbytes of data before a 2,400-bpsmodem would prove cost-effective over a 1,200-bps unit.andO;Downloading is slower between 10 PM and midnight eastern time, sothat after midnight is the best time to download.andP;  Use 'quickwords' to weave through Compuserve menus.andP;  Other tips ar included.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Compuserve Inc. (services).andO;Topic:     CompuServe (Information retrieval system)Information Storage and RetrievalOn-LineComputer ServicesCost ReductionTutorialMethodsSearch StrategySearch Cost.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>